        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(security): warn on agent skill MCP boundary drift",
        "body": "Related: #98315\n\n## What Problem This Solves\n\nResolves a problem where operators could configure per-agent skill allowlists and MCP visibility, but `openclaw security audit` would not warn when those agents still had host exec access that could reach global MCP client registries such as `skills/config/mcporter.json`.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThis adds a targeted audit finding for the risky combination instead of trying to block one `mcporter --config` command shape, which would be bypassable by alternate clients or direct script paths. The change also documents that agent skill allowlists are OpenClaw visibility/loading filters, not shell-time authorization boundaries.\n\n## User Impact\n\nOperators now get a concrete warning when per-agent skill restrictions coexist with host-exec-capable agents and configured/global MCP registries. The remediation points them toward the actual enforcement layers: deny or tightly allowlist host exec, sandbox or OS-user isolation, separate trust boundaries, and per-agent MCP credentials.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/security/audit-config-basics.test.ts` — 1 file / 7 tests passed.\n- `pnpm format:check -- src/security/audit.ts src/security/audit-config-basics.test.ts docs/gateway/security/audit-checks.md docs/tools/skills-config.md docs/tools/skills.md` — passed.\n- `git diff --check` — passed.\n- `pnpm docs:list` — passed.\n\nProof gap: `pnpm check:changed -- ...` could not run because the local Crabbox binary is `0.15.0` and the Testbox provider requires Crabbox `>=0.22.0`.\n",
